Hustle is a muscle. And so is mastery. 

The two build together, and that’s why people who are the most badass at their craft push beyond their comfort zones, practice continuously, and do the work.

Let’s rethink hustle. It isn’t all bad!

My confession... Hustle is an obsession.

I’m obsessed with helping people grow their businesses.

Just like serial entrepreneur Gary V. & Sara Blakely, Founder of @SPANX that are obsessed with their visions.

My vision is to believe strongly, care deeply, and promote progress.

The first place that needs a reframe is the good vs. bad associations with the word “Hustle.”

Hustle isn’t only associated with working 24/7 and burnout. 

Hustle is a quest to create opportunities that evolve humanity. Fueled by passion and purpose. 

https://t.co/6RMyFnvMq1

🛑So many people HATE on Hustle culture.🛑  

Instead of hating on it, here’s how you can change your relationship with “hustle” to harness it as a superpower 🧵👇
When you hear the word Hustle, what’s the first thing that comes to mind? 💭

This is why I’d argue Microsoft acquiring Activision Blizzard is proof that they have a deep understanding of the metrics of immersion & know how to “hack” the attention graph.

Making this acquisition a calculated risk vs. a bold bet.

This is why Microsoft is great at Monopoly.

What’s the one thing in common w/these individuals pursuing Web 3.0 endeavors?

They’re focused on getting & retaining their core audience's attention.

Just like Microsoft is by monetizing their audience's LTV & attention through the communities they engage in.

“Where the attention goes, the energy flows.”

All kinds of energy is flowing in the Web 3.0 direction i.e. the president of @Unilever is moving on to pursue an investment fund focused on technology megatrends, and a former exec of YouTube Gaming is joining @polygonstudios. 🌐

In the game of Monopoly the more space you snag early on, the wealthier you become over time.

Companies like Microsoft that are staking their claim in the metaverse early on (through acquisitions like this) are poising themselves to “win” in the long-run at the game of Monopoly.

Microsoft’s CEO Satya Nadella seems to agree with my theory. The metaverse is about connecting w/humans in a digital first medium.

Their press release confirms they're excited to put players & creators first. Prioritizing safety/inclusion/accessibility.

What are the essential tools you use in your day-to-day workflow? What didn't make my top 10 that is in yours?
10) Email is the bane of most people's existence. @Superhuman makes email suck less. It saves me hours every day.
9) @MiroHQ is my go-to for online collaboration. It's become the visual planning, ideation, and workshopping tool I use with my teams and clients.

7) I pretty much manage my entire life and work with @NotionHQ. It's the WIKI, Notes, and place to store, share and collaborate on knowledge and work. It's like LEGO blocks for information.
6) PASSWORDS! I've relied on @1Password for years to store and keep good habits on password management. If I can remember a password without using it the password isn't secure enough.
